e":"1399–Afdød","1395–Male":"1395–Afdød","1419–Male":"1419–Afdød","1376–Male":"1376–Afdød","1377–Female":"1377–Afdød","1377":"1377","1399":"1399","1376":"1376","1395":"1395","about 1399":"omkring 1399","1419":"1419","Fenne, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1399–":"circa 1399–Overleden","1399–Female":"1399–Overleden","1395–Male":"1395–Overleden","1419–Male":"1419–Overleden","1376–Male":"1376–Overleden","1377–Female":"1377–Overleden","1377":"1377","1399":"1399","1376":"1376","1395":"1395","about 1399":"circa 1399","1419":"1419","Fenne, Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1399–":"about 1399–Deceased","1399–Female":"1399–Deceased","1395–Male":"1395–Deceased","1419–Male":"1419–Deceased","1376–Male":"1376–Deceased","1377–Female":"1377–Deceased","1377":"1377","1399":"1399","1376":"1376","1395":"1395","about 1399":"about 1399","1419":"1419","Fenne, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane Finamour was born about 1399, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, her father, William Finamour, was 24 and her mother, Cicely Fitzstevin, was 23. She had at least 1 son with Nicholas Small."},"et":{"about 1399–":"umbes 1399–Surnud","1399–Female":"1399–Surnud","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","1419–Male":"1419–Surnud","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1377–Female":"1377–Surnud","1377":"1377","1399":"1399","1376":"1376","1395":"1395","about 1399":"umbes 1399","1419":"1419","Fenne, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1399–":"noin 1399–Kuollut","1399–Female":"1399–Kuollut","1395–Male":"1395–Kuollut","1419–Male":"1419–Kuollut","1376–Male":"1376–Kuollut","1377–Female":"1377–Kuollut","1377":"1377","1399":"1399","1376":"1376","1395":"1395","about 1399":"noin 1399","1419":"1419","Fenne, Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1399–":"environ 1399–Décédée","1399–Female":"1399–Décédée","1395–Male":"1395–Décédé","1419–Male":"1419–Décédé","1376–Male":"1376–Décédé","1377–Female":"1377–Décédée","1377":"1377","1399":"1399","1376":"1376","1395":"1395","about 1399":"environ 1399","1419":"1419","Fenne, Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Jane Finamour est née environ 1399, à Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, William Finamour, avait 24 ans et sa mère, Cicely Fitzstevin, avait 23 ans. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Nicholas Small."},"de":{"about 1399–":"um 1399–Verstorben","1399–Female":